## CONTEXT

We are building a batch file processing platform.

Files arrive in an S3 bucket:
- at different times
- at different frequencies (daily / weekly / monthly / ad hoc)
- in different sizes (MB to multi-GB)

We process these files using:

### Tech stack:
- Control-M (orchestration)
- Spring Boot + Spring Batch
- ECS (compute)
- AWS Batch (job execution)
- PostgreSQL (primary database)

### Design constraints (resolve explicitly — avoid two incompatible designs)

- **Scheduling vs event-driven:** State whether Control-M is the system of record for schedules and dependencies, whether S3/EventBridge is used only to signal work (e.g. enqueue), or another split. Document who may submit work and how duplicates are prevented.
- **AWS Batch vs ECS:** Clarify the relationship — e.g. AWS Batch runs Spring Batch jobs on ECS (Fargate/EC2) as the compute plane; call out any **additional** long-running ECS services (if any) and their role vs Batch jobs.

---

## KEY PROBLEM

If multiple files land in S3 at the same time:
- multiple jobs may get triggered
- AWS Batch may scale aggressively
- PostgreSQL may get overwhelmed
- duplicate processing may occur
- system may become unstable

You must design a system that prevents this.

